ies featured in this volume introduce three distinct archetypes: the cultural personality, the tycoon, and the collective enterprise. These portraits reveal how changes in social and economic conditions created the fertile soil for business success; conditions that are similar to those emerging in China today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBusinesspeoplezChinavCase studies. 0aBusinesspeoplezSoutheast AsiavCase studies. 0aCultural industrieszChinavCase studies. 0aCultural industrieszSoutheast AsiavCase studies. 0aEntrepreneurshipzChinavCase studies. 0aEntrepreneurshipzSoutheast AsiavCase studies. 7aART / Asian / General.2bisacsh1 aCulp, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFong, Grace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGungwu, Wang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Michael Gibbs, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLean, Eugenia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLin, Chua Ai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRea, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRea, Christopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aReed, Christopher A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTheng, Sin Yee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVolland, Nicolai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVolland, Nicolai, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYung, Sai-Shing, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2015z97831112740270